erve in Healthy Aging and Dementia -- tV. Conclusion -- tConcluding Remarks and Future Directions -- tIndex -- tAbout the Editors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book pioneers the study of bilingualism across the lifespan and in all its diverse forms. In framing the newest research within a lifespan perspective, the editors highlight the importance of considering an individual's age in researching how bilingualism affects language acquisition and cognitive development. A key theme is the variability among bilinguals, which may be due to a host of individual and sociocultural factors, including the degree to which bilingualism is valued within a particular context.Thus, this book is a call for language researchers, psychologists, and educators to pursue a better understanding of bilingualism in our increasingly global society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aApplied Linguistics.  aBilingualism.  aCognitive Linguistics.  aPsycholinguistics.1 aConboy, Barbara T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Hilary D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFennell, Christopher T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlynn, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Max R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGathercole, Virginia C. Mueller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenesee, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGullifer, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudon